---++ UML

UML defines the structural modeling diagrams, 6 in 1.x and 13 in 2.x.

<table width="100%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="0" border="0"><tbody><tr><td width="3%" align="center" valign="top">- </td> <td width="96%"> The User Interaction or [[http://www.sparxsystems.com/resources/tutorial/use_case_model.html][Use Case Model]] - describes the boundary and interaction between the system and users. Corresponds in some respects to a requirements model. </td> </tr> <tr> <td align="center" valign="top"> - </td> <td> The Interaction or Communication Model - describes how objects in the system will interact with each other to get work done. </td> </tr> <tr> <td align="center" valign="top"> - </td> <td> The State or [[http://www.sparxsystems.com/resources/tutorial/dynamic_model.html][Dynamic Model]] - State charts describe the states or conditions that classes assume over time. Activity graphs describe the workflows the system will implement. </td> </tr> <tr> <td align="center" valign="top"> - </td> <td> The [[http://www.sparxsystems.com/resources/tutorial/logical_model.html][Logical or Class Model]] - describes the classes and objects that will make up the system. </td> </tr> <tr> <td align="center" valign="top"> - </td> <td> The Physical [[http://www.sparxsystems.com/resources/tutorial/component_model.html][Component Model]] - describes the software (and sometimes hardware components) that make up the system. </td> </tr> <tr> <td align="center" valign="top"> - </td> <td> The [[http://www.sparxsystems.com/resources/tutorial/physical_models.html][Physical Deployment Model]] - describes the physical architecture and the deployment of components on that hardware architecture. </td></tr></tbody></table>

